      "contentSections": [
        {
          "type": "tier-comparison",
          "title": "Program Comparison",
          "content": {
            "programs": [
              {
                "name": "QMB (Qualified Medicare Beneficiary)",
                "incomeLimit": "$1,350/month (individual), $1,824/month (couple)",
                "benefits": "Pays Medicare Part A & B premiums, deductibles, coinsurance, and copays",
                "notes": "Most comprehensive coverage"
              },
              {
                "name": "SLMB (Specified Low-Income Beneficiary)",
                "incomeLimit": "~$1,526/month (individual), higher for couples",
                "benefits": "Pays Medicare Part B premiums only",
                "notes": "Must have both Medicare Parts A and B"
              },
              {
                "name": "QI (Qualifying Individual)",
                "incomeLimit": "$1,781/month (individual), $2,400/month (couple)",
                "benefits": "Pays Medicare Part B premiums only",
                "notes": "Limited funding, first-come first-served, annual reapplication required"
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one keep their house and car if they qualify?",
          "answer": "Yes. The primary home is completely exempt from asset limits regardless of value. One vehicle per household is also exempt. Only countable assets like bank accounts, CDs, and investments count toward the $9,430 limit for individuals."
        },
        {
          "question": "What's the real difference between these three programs?",
          "answer": "QMB covers everything Medicare doesn't pay — premiums, deductibles, copays at doctors and hospitals. SLMB and QI only cover the monthly Medicare Part B premium (around $185 in 2026). QMB has the lowest income limit but provides the most comprehensive coverage."
        },
        {
          "question": "How likely is my loved one to get into the QI program?",
          "answer": "QI has limited federal funding allocated to South Dakota each year. Previous recipients get priority, but must reapply annually. New applicants have the best chance by applying early in the calendar year when funding is available."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for my loved one if they have dementia?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can apply on behalf of elderly loved ones. You'll need to provide all required documentation and may need to show legal authority to act on their behalf, such as power of attorney."
        },
        {
          "question": "Will this affect my loved one's other benefits like Social Security?",
          "answer": "No, Medicare Savings Programs don't affect Social Security, pensions, or other income. In fact, enrollment automatically qualifies your loved one for Extra Help with prescription drug costs, adding more savings."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's income changes after enrollment?",
          "answer": "You must report significant income changes to DSS within 30 days. Small changes may not affect eligibility, but large increases could result in losing benefits. All programs require annual renewal regardless."
        },
        {
          "question": "How does the $20 income disregard work?",
          "answer": "South Dakota excludes the first $20 of monthly income when calculating eligibility. So if your loved one receives $1,370 in Social Security, only $1,350 counts toward the QMB income limit of $1,350/month."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one have both Medicare Savings Programs and regular Medicaid?",
          "answer": "Yes, many people qualify for both. Having QMB, SLMB, or QI can actually help your loved one qualify for full Medicaid benefits in some cases, since Medicare costs are already covered."
        }
      ],
