      "intro": "If your loved one is 60+ and lives on a fixed income in South Dakota, they can receive a free monthly box of USDA foods through the Commodity Supplemental Food Program (CSFP). Each box contains non-perishable items like cheese, juice, oats, cereal, rice, pasta, peanut butter, beans, canned meat or fish, fruits, vegetables, and often a canned entree like beef stew. Income must be at or below 150% of federal poverty guidelines — higher than SNAP's 130% limit.\n\nThis program is separate from SNAP benefits, so your loved one can receive both simultaneously if they qualify for each. Because CSFP uses local distribution sites with varying schedules, you'll need to call your regional agency to find pickup locations and times in your area.\n\nUnlike regular food stamps, CSFP provides a fixed monthly box rather than a card for grocery shopping. The program is designed specifically for seniors and has no asset limits — only income matters for qualification.",
