      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one keep their house if it's worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes, the primary home is exempt from the $2,000 asset limit if your loved one intends to return and the equity is $730,000 or less. If your loved one's spouse, minor child, or disabled child lives there, there's no equity limit. The house only counts toward the $2,000 if your loved one has no intent to return and none of these family members live there."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long is the waitlist really?",
          "answer": "The program caps enrollment at 1,834 people statewide, so waitlists develop when full. South Dakota doesn't publish specific wait times, but they vary by region and your loved one's priority level. Call Dakota at Home at (833) 663-9673 for current estimates in your area."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for my loved one if they have dementia?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can apply on behalf of parents who cannot manage their own affairs due to cognitive impairment. You may need to provide legal documentation like power of attorney. The Case Management Specialist will work with you as the responsible party throughout the process."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's income increases after enrollment?",
          "answer": "Your loved one must report income changes within 30 days. If monthly income exceeds $2,901, they'll lose HOPE Waiver eligibility. However, if the increase is temporary or they qualify for income deductions, they may maintain eligibility. The case manager will reassess annually."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one get both HOPE Waiver and regular Medicaid services?",
          "answer": "HOPE Waiver recipients automatically qualify for standard Medicaid benefits like doctor visits, hospital care, and prescriptions. The waiver adds home and community services on top of regular Medicaid. You cannot combine HOPE with other Medicaid waivers simultaneously."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one needs more care than the waiver provides?",
          "answer": "The case manager reassesses needs annually and can adjust service levels. If your loved one's needs exceed what home and community services can safely provide, they may need to transition to nursing facility care. The waiver cannot continue if nursing facility placement becomes necessary for safety."
        },
        {
          "question": "Do I have to use specific providers for respite care?",
          "answer": "Yes, all providers must have contracts with South Dakota DHS and Medicaid enrollment for long-term services and supports. Your case manager will provide a list of approved providers in your area. You cannot hire family members or unlicensed individuals through the waiver."
        },
        {
          "question": "What's the difference between HOPE Waiver and Family Support 360?",
          "answer": "The research sources don't clearly define Family Support 360 as separate from HOPE Waiver services. Call Dakota at Home at (833) 663-9673 to clarify whether Family Support 360 is a branded component of HOPE Waiver or a separate caregiver support program with different eligibility rules."
        }
      ],
